# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sre-observability
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] In the fields of information technology and systems management, **application performance management** (**APM**) is the monitoring and management of the performance and availability of software applications.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] APM strives to detect and diagnose complex application performance problems to maintain an expected level of service.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The term monitoring was replaced by many tool vendors by the term Observability.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Often, monitoring is seen as the technical process of data collection, whereas observability is seen as the capability to understand a systems behavior.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Two sets of performance metrics are closely monitored.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The first set of performance metrics defines the performance experienced by end-users of the application.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] One example of performance is average response times under peak load.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The second set of performance metrics measures the computational resources used by the application for the load, indicating whether there is adequate capacity to support the load, as well as possible locations of a performance bottleneck.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Measurement of these quantities establishes an empirical performance baseline for the application.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The baseline can then be used to detect changes in performance.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Changes in performance can be correlated with external events and subsequently used to predict future changes in application performance.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The use of APM is common for Web applications, which lends itself best to the more detailed monitoring techniques.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] In addition to measuring response time for a user, response times for components of a Web application can also be monitored to help pinpoint causes of delay.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] There also exist HTTP appliances that can decode transaction-specific response times at the Web server layer of the application.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Measuring application performance causes overhead, that might also influence the user experience.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The overhead can be reduced by several technical measures, including reducing the amount of monitored events and aggregation of data before serialization.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Since the first half of 2013, APM has entered into a period of intense competition in technology and strategy with a multiplicity of vendors and viewpoints.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] This has caused an upheaval in the marketplace with vendors from unrelated backgrounds (including network monitoring, systems management, application instrumentation, and web performance monitoring) adopting messaging around APM.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] As a result, the term APM has become diluted and has evolved into a concept for managing application performance across many diverse computing platforms, rather than a single market.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] With so many vendors to choose from, selecting one can be a challenge.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] It is important to evaluate each carefully to ensure its capabilities meet your needs.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Two challenges for implementing APM are (1) it can be difficult to instrument an application to monitor application performance, especially among components of an application, and (2) applications can be virtualized, which increases the variability of the measurements.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] To alleviate the first problem application service management (ASM) provides an application-centric approach, where business service performance visibility is a key objective.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The second aspect present in distributed, virtual and cloud-based applications poses a unique challenge for application performance monitoring because most of the key system components are no longer hosted on a single machine.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Each function is now likely to have been designed as an Internet service that runs on multiple virtualized systems.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The applications themselves are very likely to be moving from one system to another to meet service-level objectives and deal with momentary outages.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Applications themselves are becoming increasingly difficult to manage as they move toward highly distributed, multi-tier, multi-element constructs that in many cases rely on application development frameworks such as .NET or Java.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The APM Conceptual Framework was designed to help prioritize an approach on what to focus on first for quick implementation and overall understanding of the five-dimensional APM model.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The framework slide outlines three areas of focus for each dimension and describes their potential benefits.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Measuring the transit of traffic from user request to data and back again is part of capturing the end-user experience (EUE).
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] The outcome of this measuring is referred to as Real-time Application monitoring (aka Top-Down monitoring), which has two components, passive and active.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Passive monitoring is usually an agentless appliance implemented using network port mirroring.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] A key feature to consider is the ability to support multi-component analytics (e.g., database, client/browser).
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Active monitoring, on the other hand, consists of synthetic probes and web robots predefined to report system availability and business transactions.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Active monitoring is a good complement to passive monitoring; together, these two components help provide visibility into application health during off-peak hours when transaction volume is low.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] When preparing to implement a runtime application architecture, it is necessary to ensure that up/down monitoring is in place for all nodes and servers within the environment (aka, bottom-up monitoring).
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] This helps lay the foundation for event correlation and provides the basis for a general understanding of how network topologies interact with application architectures.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Focus on user-defined transactions or the URL page definitions that have some meaning to the business community.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] For example, if there are 200 to 300 unique page definitions for a given application, group them into 8–12 high-level categories.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] This allows for meaningful SLA reports, and provides trending information on application performance from a business perspective: start with broad categories and refine them over time.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] For a deeper understanding, see Business transaction management.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Deep dive component monitoring (DDCM) requires an agent installation and is generally targeted at middleware, focusing on web, application, and messaging servers.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] It should provide a real-time view of the J2EE and .NET stacks, tying them back to the user-defined business transactions.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] A robust monitor shows a clear path from code execution (e.g., spring and struts) to the URL rendered, and finally to the user request.
[src:sre-observability/application-performance-management] Since DDCM is closely related to the second dimension in the APM model, most products in this field also provide application discovery dependency mapping (ADDM) as part of their offering.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] In software development, the ability of a given software to tolerate failures while still ensuring adequate quality of service—often termed *resilience*—is typically specified as a requirement.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] However, development teams may fail to meet this requirement due to factors such as short deadlines or lack of domain knowledge.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Chaos engineering encompasses techniques aimed at meeting resilience requirements.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Chaos engineering can be used to achieve resilience against infrastructure failures, network failures, and application failures; the latter includes resilience to unhandled exceptions.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Calculating how much confidence we have in the interconnected complex systems that are put into production environments requires operational readiness metrics.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Operational readiness can be evaluated using chaos engineering simulations.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Solutions for increasing the resilience and operational readiness of a platform include strengthening the backup, restore, network file transfer, failover capabilities and overall security of the environment.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] An evaluation to induce chaos in a Kubernetes environment terminated random pods receiving data from edge devices in data centers while processing analytics on a big data network.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] The pods' recovery time was a resiliency metric that estimated the response time.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] While MacWrite and MacPaint were being developed for the first Apple Macintosh computer, Steve Capps created "Monkey", a desk accessory which randomly generated user interface events at high speed, simulating a monkey frantically banging the keyboard and moving and clicking the mouse.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] It was promptly put to use for debugging by generating errors for programmers to fix, because automated testing was not possible; the first Macintosh had too little free memory space for anything more sophisticated.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] While working to improve website reliability at Amazon, Jesse Robbins created "Game day", an initiative that increases reliability by purposefully creating major failures on a regular basis.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Robbins has said it was inspired by firefighter training and research in other fields lessons in complex systems, reliability engineering.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] While at Google, Kripa Krishnan created a similar program to Amazon's Game day (see above) called "DiRT" (Disaster Recovery Testing).
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Jason Cahoon, a Site Reliability Engineer at Google, contributed a chapter on Google DiRT in the "Chaos Engineering" book and described the system at the GOTOpia 2021 conference.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] While overseeing Netflix's migration to the cloud in 2011 Nora Jones, Casey Rosenthal, and Greg Orzell expanded the discipline while working together at Netflix by setting up a tool that would cause breakdowns in their production environment, the environment used by Netflix customers.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] By regularly "killing" random instances of a software service, it was possible to test a redundant architecture to verify that a server failure did not noticeably impact customers.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] The concept of chaos engineering is close to the one of Phoenix Servers, first introduced by Martin Fowler in 2012.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] The code behind Chaos Monkey was released by Netflix in 2012 under an Apache 2.0 license.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Voyages-sncf.com's 2017 "Day of Chaos" gamified simulating pre-production failures to present at the 2017 DevOps REX conference.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Founded in 2019, Steadybit popularized pre-production chaos and reliability engineering.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Its open-source Reliability Hub extends Steadybit.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Proofdock can inject infrastructure, platform, and application failures on Microsoft Azure DevOps.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Gremlin is a "failure-as-a-service" platform.
[src:sre-observability/chaos-engineering] Facebook's Project Storm simulates datacenter failures for natural disaster resistance.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance specifically refers to a system's capability to handle faults without any degradation or downtime.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In the event of an error, end-users remain unaware of any issues.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Conversely, a system that experiences errors with some interruption in service or graceful degradation of performance is termed 'resilient'.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In resilience, the system adapts to the error, maintaining service but acknowledging a certain impact on performance.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Typically, fault tolerance describes computer systems, ensuring the overall system remains functional despite hardware or software issues.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Non-computing examples include structures that retain their integrity despite damage from fatigue, corrosion or impact.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The first known fault-tolerant computer was SAPO, built in 1951 in Czechoslovakia by Antonín Svoboda.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Its basic design was magnetic drums connected via relays, with a voting method of memory error detection (triple modular redundancy).
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Several other machines were developed along this line, mostly for military use.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Computers with a high amount of runtime that would be under heavy use, such as many of the supercomputers used by insurance companies for their probability monitoring.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Most of the development in the so-called LLNM (Long Life, No Maintenance) computing was done by NASA during the 1960s, in preparation for Project Apollo and other research aspects.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] NASA's first machine went into a space observatory, and their second attempt, the JSTAR computer, was used in Voyager.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] This computer had a backup of memory arrays to use memory recovery methods and thus it was called the Jet Propulsion Laboratory Self-Testing-And-Repairing computer.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] It could detect its own errors and fix them or use redundant modules as needed.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The computer is still working, as of early 2022.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Hyper-dependable computers were pioneered mostly by aircraft manufacturers, nuclear power companies, and the railroad industry in the United States.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] These entities needed computers with massive amounts of uptime that would fail gracefully enough during a fault to allow continued operation, while relying on constant human monitoring of computer output to detect faults.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] IBM developed the first computer of this kind for NASA for guidance of Saturn V rockets.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Later, BNSF, Unisys, and General Electric built their own.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In the 1970s, much work happened in the field.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] For instance, F14 CADC had built-in self-test and redundancy.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In general, the early efforts at fault-tolerant designs were focused mainly on internal diagnosis, where a fault would indicate something was failing and a worker could replace it.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] SAPO, for instance, had a method by which faulty memory drums would emit a noise before failure.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Later efforts showed that to be fully effective, the system had to be self-repairing and diagnosing – isolating a fault and then implementing a redundant backup while alerting a need for repair.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] This is known as N-model redundancy, where faults cause automatic fail-safes and a warning to the operator, and it is still the most common form of level one fault-tolerant design in use today.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Voting was another initial method, as discussed above, with multiple redundant backups operating constantly and checking each other's results.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] For example, if four components reported an answer of 5 and one component reported an answer of 6, the other four would "vote" that the fifth component was faulty and have it taken out of service.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] This is called M out of N majority voting.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Historically, the trend has been to move away from N-model and toward M out of N, as the complexity of systems and the difficulty of ensuring the transitive state from fault-negative to fault-positive did not disrupt operations.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers, in 1976 and Stratus Technologies were among the first companies specializing in the design of fault-tolerant computer systems for online transaction processing.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Hardware fault tolerance sometimes requires that broken parts be removed and replaced with new parts while the system is still operational (in computing known as *hot swapping*).
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Such a system implemented with a single backup is known as **single point tolerant** and represents the vast majority of fault-tolerant systems.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In such systems the mean time between failures should be long enough for the operators to have sufficient time to fix the broken devices (mean time to repair) before the backup also fails.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] It is helpful if the time between failures is as long as possible, but this is not specifically required in a fault-tolerant system.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Fault tolerance is notably successful in computer applications.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Tandem Computers built their entire business on such machines, which used single-point tolerance to create their NonStop systems with uptimes measured in years.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Fail-safe architectures may encompass also the computer software, for example by process replication.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Data formats may also be designed to degrade gracefully.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Hyper Text Markup Language (HTML) for example, is designed to be forward compatible, allowing Web browsers to ignore new and unsupported HTML entities without causing the document to be unusable.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Additionally, proper user interface design mandates that websites provide an optional lightweight front end that does not rely on JavaScript and has a minimal layout, to ensure wide accessibility and outreach.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A highly fault-tolerant system might continue at the same level of performance even though one or more components have failed.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] For example, a building with a backup electrical generator will provide the same voltage to wall outlets even if the grid power fails.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A system that is designed to fail safe, or fail-secure, or **fail gracefully**, whether it functions at a reduced level or fails completely, does so in a way that protects people, property, or data from injury, damage, intrusion, or disclosure.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In computers, a program might fail-safe by executing a graceful exit (as opposed to an uncontrolled crash) to prevent data corruption after an error occurs.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A similar distinction is made between "failing well" and "failing badly".
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A system designed to experience **graceful degradation**, or to **fail soft** (used in computing, similar to "fail safe") operates at a reduced level of performance after some component fails.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] For example, if grid power fails, a building may operate lighting at reduced levels or elevators at reduced speeds.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In computing, if insufficient network bandwidth is available to stream an online video, a lower-resolution version might be streamed in place of the high-resolution version.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Progressive enhancement is another example, where web pages are available in a basic functional format for older, small-screen, or limited-capability web browsers, but in an enhanced version for browsers capable of handling additional technologies or that have a larger display.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In fault-tolerant computer systems, programs that are considered robust are designed to continue operation despite an error, exception, or invalid input, instead of failing completely.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Software brittleness is the opposite of robustness.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Resilient networks continue to transmit data despite the failure of some links or nodes.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Resilient buildings and infrastructure are likewise expected to prevent complete failure in situations like earthquakes, floods, or collisions.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A system with high failure transparency will alert users that a component failure has occurred, even if it continues to operate with full performance, so that failure can be repaired or imminent complete failure anticipated.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Likewise, a fail-fast component is designed to report at the first point of failure, rather than generating reports when downstream components fail.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] This allows easier diagnosis of the underlying problem, and may prevent improper operation in a broken state.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A **single fault condition** is a situation where one means for protection against a hazard is defective.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] If a single fault condition results unavoidably in another single fault condition, the two failures are considered one single fault condition.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Providing fault-tolerant design for every component is normally not an option.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Associated redundancy brings a number of penalties: increase in weight, size, power consumption, cost, as well as time to design, verify, and test.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] An example of a component that passes all the tests is a car's occupant restraint system.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] While the *primary* occupant restraint system is not normally thought of, it is gravity.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] If the vehicle rolls over or undergoes severe g-forces, then this primary method of occupant restraint may fail.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Restraining the occupants during such an accident is absolutely critical to safety, so the first test is passed.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Accidents causing occupant ejection were quite common before seat belts, so the second test is passed.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The cost of a redundant restraint method like seat belts is quite low, both economically and in terms of weight and space, so the third test is passed.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Therefore, adding seat belts to all vehicles is an excellent idea.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Other "supplemental restraint systems", such as airbags, are more expensive and so pass that test by a smaller margin.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] It would also be prohibitively costly to further double-up the main components and they would add considerable weight.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] However, the similarly critical systems for actuating the brakes under driver control are inherently less robust, generally using a cable (which can rust, stretch, jam, or snap) or hydraulic fluid (which can leak, boil and develop bubbles, or absorb water and thus lose effectiveness).
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The cumulatively unlikely combination of total foot brake failure with the need for harsh braking in an emergency will likely result in a collision, but still one at lower speed than would otherwise have been the case.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In comparison with the foot pedal activated service brake, the parking brake itself is a less critical item, and unless it is being used as a one-time backup for the footbrake, will not cause immediate danger if it is found to be nonfunctional at the moment of application.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, on shallow gradients, the transmission can be shifted into Park, Reverse or First gear, and the transmission lock / engine compression used to hold it stationary, as there is no need for them to include the sophistication to first bring the vehicle to a halt.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] On motorcycles, a similar level of fail-safety is provided by simpler methods; first, the front and rear brake systems are entirely separate, regardless of their method of activation (that can be cable, rod or hydraulic), allowing one system to fail entirely while leaving the other unaffected.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Fault isolation to the failing component – When a failure occurs, the system must be able to isolate the failure to the offending component.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] This requires the addition of dedicated failure detection mechanisms that exist only for the purpose of fault isolation.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Recovery from a fault condition requires classifying the fault or failing component.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Faults are commonly categorized by their locality (internal or external to the system), cause (natural or human-made), duration (permanent or transient), and effect on system behavior.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Fault containment to prevent propagation of the failure – Some failure mechanisms can cause a system to fail by propagating the failure to the rest of the system.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] An example of this kind of failure is the "rogue transmitter" that can swamp legitimate communication in a system and cause overall system failure.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Firewalls or other mechanisms that isolate a rogue transmitter or failing component to protect the system are required.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Availability of reversion modes, which is the abandonment of recent changes, usually to software, that bring a system back to reasonably proper behavior and function.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In addition, fault-tolerant systems are characterized in terms of both planned service outages and unplanned service outages.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] These are usually measured at the application level and not just at a hardware level.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The figure of merit is called availability and is expressed as a percentage.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] For example, a five nines system would statistically provide 99.999% availability.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Fault-tolerant systems are typically based on the concept of redundancy.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Research into the kinds of tolerances needed for critical systems involves a large amount of interdisciplinary work.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The more complex the system, the more carefully all possible interactions have to be considered and prepared for.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] All implementations of RAID, redundant array of independent disks, except RAID 0, are examples of a fault-tolerant storage device that uses data redundancy.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A lockstep fault-tolerant machine uses replicated elements operating in parallel.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] At any time, all the replications of each element should be in the same state.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The same inputs are provided to each replication, and the same outputs are expected.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The outputs of the replications are compared using a voting circuit.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A machine with two replications of each element is termed dual modular redundant (DMR).
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can then only detect a mismatch and recovery relies on other methods.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A machine with three replications of each element is termed triple modular redundant (TMR).
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The voting circuit can determine which replication is in error when a two-to-one vote is observed.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In this case, the voting circuit can output the correct result, and discard the erroneous version.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] After this, the internal state of the erroneous replication is assumed to be different from that of the other two, and the voting circuit can switch to a DMR mode.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] This model can be applied to any larger number of replications.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Lockstep fault-tolerant machines are most easily made fully synchronous, with each gate of each replication making the same state transition on the same edge of the clock, and the clocks to the replications being exactly in phase.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] However, it is possible to build lockstep systems without this requirement.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Bringing the replications into synchrony requires making their internal stored states the same.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] They can be started from a fixed initial state, such as the reset state.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Alternatively, the internal state of one replica can be copied to another replica.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] One variant of DMR is **pair-and-spare**.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Two replicated elements operate in lockstep as a pair, with a voting circuit that detects any mismatch between their operations and outputs a signal indicating that there is an error.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Another pair operates exactly the same way.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] A final circuit selects the output of the pair that does not proclaim that it is in error.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Pair-and-spare requires four replicas rather than the three of TMR, but has been used commercially.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The approach has performance costs: because the technique rewrites code to insert dynamic checks for address validity, execution time will increase by 80% to 500%.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Recovery shepherding is a lightweight technique to enable software programs to recover from otherwise fatal errors such as null pointer dereference and divide by zero.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Comparing to the failure oblivious computing technique, recovery shepherding works on the compiled program binary directly and does not need to recompile to program.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] It uses the just-in-time binary instrumentation framework Pin.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] It attaches to the application process when an error occurs, repairs the execution, tracks the repair effects as the execution continues, contains the repair effects within the application process, and detaches from the process after all repair effects are flushed from the process state.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] It does not interfere with the normal execution of the program and therefore incurs negligible overhead.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] For 17 of 18 systematically collected real world null-dereference and divide-by-zero errors, a prototype implementation enables the application to continue to execute to provide acceptable output and service to its users on the error-triggering inputs.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The circuit breaker design pattern is a technique to avoid catastrophic failures in distributed systems.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Redundancy is the provision of functional capabilities that would be unnecessary in a fault-free environment.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] This can consist of backup components that automatically "kick in" if one component fails.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] For example, large cargo trucks can lose a tire without any major consequences.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] They have many tires, and no one tire is critical (with the exception of the front tires, which are used to steer, but generally carry less load, each and in total, than the other four to 16, so are less likely to fail).
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The idea of incorporating redundancy in order to improve the reliability of a system was pioneered by John von Neumann in the 1950s.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Two kinds of redundancy are possible: space redundancy and time redundancy.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy provides additional components, functions, or data items that are unnecessary for fault-free operation.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] Space redundancy is further classified into hardware, software and information redundancy, depending on the type of redundant resources added to the system.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] In time redundancy the computation or data transmission is repeated and the result is compared to a stored copy of the previous result.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] The current terminology for this kind of testing is referred to as In Service Fault Tolerance Testing or ISFTT for short.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] There is a difference between fault tolerance and systems that rarely have problems.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] For instance, the Western Electric crossbar systems had failure rates of two hours per forty years, and therefore were highly *fault resistant*.
[src:sre-observability/fault-tolerance] But when a fault did occur, they stopped operating completely, and therefore were not *fault tolerant*.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] There is now more dependence on these systems as a result of modernization.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] For example, to carry out their regular daily tasks, hospitals and data centers need their systems to be highly available.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Availability refers to the ability of the user to access a service or system, whether to submit new work, update or modify existing work, or retrieve the results of previous work.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] If a user cannot access the system, it is considered *unavailable from the user's perspective*.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The term *downtime* is generally used to refer to describe periods when a system is unavailable.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] As such, network resilience touches a very wide range of topics.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] In order to increase the resilience of a given communication network, the probable challenges and risks have to be identified and appropriate resilience metrics have to be defined for the service to be protected.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The importance of network resilience is continuously increasing, as communication networks are becoming a fundamental component in the operation of critical infrastructures.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Consequently, recent efforts focus on interpreting and improving network and computing resilience with applications to critical infrastructures.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] As an example, one can consider as a resilience objective the provisioning of services over the network, instead of the services of the network itself.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] This may require coordinated response from both the network and from the services running on top of the network.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Resilience and survivability are interchangeably used according to the specific context of a given study.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] There are three principles of systems design in reliability engineering that can help achieve high availability.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] In redundant systems, the crossover point itself tends to become a single point of failure.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Reliable systems must provide for reliable crossover.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] If the two principles above are observed, then a user may never see a failure – but the maintenance activity must.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A distinction can be made between scheduled and unscheduled downtime.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Typically, scheduled downtime is a result of maintenance that is disruptive to system operation and usually cannot be avoided with a currently installed system design.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Scheduled downtime events might include patches to system software that require a reboot or system configuration changes that only take effect upon a reboot.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] In general, scheduled downtime is usually the result of some logical, management-initiated event.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Unscheduled downtime events typically arise from some physical event, such as a hardware or software failure or environmental anomaly.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] If users can be warned away from scheduled downtimes, then the distinction is useful.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] But if the requirement is for true high availability, then downtime is downtime whether or not it is scheduled.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Many computing sites exclude scheduled downtime from availability calculations, assuming that it has little or no impact upon the computing user community.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] By doing this, they can claim to have phenomenally high availability, which might give the illusion of continuous availability.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] For certain systems, scheduled downtime does not matter, for example, system downtime at an office building after everybody has gone home for the night.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Availability is usually expressed as a percentage of uptime in a given year.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The following table shows the downtime that will be allowed for a particular percentage of availability, presuming that the system is required to operate continuously.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Service level agreements often refer to monthly downtime or availability in order to calculate service credits to match monthly billing cycles.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The following table shows the translation from a given availability percentage to the corresponding amount of time a system would be unavailable.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Availability is often quoted in terms of "nines", with 90% availability being called "one nine", 99% "two nines", 99.9% "three nines" and so on.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] As the number of nines gets larger, the availability targets get exponentially more stringent.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The terms uptime and availability are often used interchangeably but do not always refer to the same thing.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] For example, a system can be "up" with its services not "available" in the case of a network outage.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Or a system undergoing software maintenance can be "available" to be worked on by a system administrator, but its services do not appear "up" to the end user or customer.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A simple mnemonic rule states that *5 nines* allows approximately 5 minutes of downtime per year.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Variants can be derived by multiplying or dividing by 10: 4 nines is 50 minutes and 3 nines is 500 minutes.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] In the opposite direction, 6 nines is 0.5 minutes (30 sec) and 7 nines is 3 seconds.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Another memory trick to calculate the allowed downtime duration for an " n -nines" availability percentage is to use the formula $8.64\times 10^{4-n}$ seconds per day.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] For example, 90% ("one nine") yields the exponent $4-1=3$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{3}$ seconds per day.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Also, 99.999% ("five nines") gives the exponent $4-5=-1$ , and therefore the allowed downtime is $8.64\times 10^{-1}$ seconds per day.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Percentages of a particular order of magnitude are sometimes referred to by the number of nines or "class of nines" in the digits.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] For example, electricity that is delivered without interruptions (blackouts, brownouts or surges) 99.999% of the time would have 5 nines reliability, or class five.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] In particular, the term is used in connection with mainframes or enterprise computing, often as part of a service-level agreement.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Similarly, percentages ending in a 5 have conventional names, traditionally the number of nines, then "five", so 99.95% is "three nines five", abbreviated 3N5.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] This is casually referred to as "three and a half nines", but this is incorrect: a 5 is only a factor of 2, while a 9 is a factor of 10, so a 5 is 0.3 nines (per below formula: $\log _{10}2\approx 0.3$ ): 99.95% availability is 3.3 nines, not 3.5 nines.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] More simply, going from 99.9% availability to 99.95% availability is a factor of 2 (0.1% to 0.05% unavailability), but going from 99.95% to 99.99% availability is a factor of 5 (0.05% to 0.01% unavailability), over twice as much.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A similar measurement is sometimes used to describe the purity of substances.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] In general, the number of nines is not often used by a network engineer when modeling and measuring availability because it is hard to apply in formula.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] More often, the unavailability expressed as a probability (like 0.00001), or a downtime per year is quoted.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Availability specified as a number of nines is often seen in marketing documents.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The use of the "nines" has been called into question, since it does not appropriately reflect that the impact of unavailability varies with its time of occurrence.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] For large amounts of 9s, the "unavailability" index (measure of downtime rather than uptime) is easier to handle.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] For example, this is why an "unavailability" rather than availability metric is used in hard disk or data link bit error rates.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Sometimes the humorous term "nine fives" (55.5555555%) is used to contrast with "five nines" (99.999%), though this is not an actual goal, but rather a sarcastic reference to something totally failing to meet any reasonable target.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Availability measurement is subject to some degree of interpretation.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A system that has been up for 365 days in a non-leap year might have been eclipsed by a network failure that lasted for 9 hours during a peak usage period; the user community will see the system as unavailable, whereas the system administrator will claim 100% uptime.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] However, given the true definition of availability, the system will be approximately 99.9% available, or three nines (8751 hours of available time out of 8760 hours per non-leap year).
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Also, systems experiencing performance problems are often deemed partially or entirely unavailable by users, even when the systems are continuing to function.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Similarly, unavailability of select application functions might go unnoticed by administrators yet be devastating to users – a true availability measure is holistic.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Availability must be measured to be determined, ideally with comprehensive monitoring tools ("instrumentation") that are themselves highly available.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] An alternative metric is mean time between failures (MTBF).
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Recovery time (or estimated time of repair (ETR), also known as recovery time objective (RTO) is closely related to availability, that is the total time required for a planned outage or the time required to fully recover from an unplanned outage.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Another metric is mean time to recovery (MTTR).
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Recovery time could be infinite with certain system designs and failures, i.e. full recovery is impossible.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] One such example is a fire or flood that destroys a data center and its systems when there is no secondary disaster recovery data center.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Another related concept is data availability, that is the degree to which databases and other information storage systems faithfully record and report system transactions.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Information management often focuses separately on data availability, or Recovery Point Objective, in order to determine acceptable (or actual) data loss with various failure events.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Some users can tolerate application service interruptions but cannot tolerate data loss.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A service level agreement ("SLA") formalizes an organization's availability objectives and requirements.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] High availability is one of the primary requirements of the control systems in unmanned vehicles and autonomous maritime vessels.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] If the controlling system becomes unavailable, the Ground Combat Vehicle (GCV) or ASW Continuous Trail Unmanned Vessel (ACTUV) would be lost.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] On one hand, adding more components to an overall system design can undermine efforts to achieve high availability because complex systems inherently have more potential failure points and are more difficult to implement correctly.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] More advanced system designs allow for systems to be patched and upgraded without compromising service availability (see load balancing and failover).
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] High availability requires less human intervention to restore operation in complex systems; the reason for this being that the most common cause for outages is human error.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] On the other hand, redundancy is used to create systems with high levels of availability (e.g. popular ecommerce websites).
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] In this case it is required to have high levels of failure detectability and avoidance of common cause failures.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] If redundant parts are used in parallel and have independent failure (e.g. by not being within the same data center), they can exponentially increase the availability and make the overall system highly available.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] So for example if each of your components has only 50% availability, by using 10 of components in parallel, you can achieve 99.9023% availability.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Two kinds of redundancy are passive redundancy and active redundancy.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Passive redundancy is used to achieve high availability by including enough excess capacity in the design to accommodate a performance decline.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The simplest example is a boat with two separate engines driving two separate propellers.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The boat continues toward its destination despite failure of a single engine or propeller.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A more complex example is multiple redundant power generation facilities within a large system involving electric power transmission.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Malfunction of single components is not considered to be a failure unless the resulting performance decline exceeds the specification limits for the entire system.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Active redundancy is used in complex systems to achieve high availability with no performance decline.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Multiple items of the same kind are incorporated into a design that includes a method to detect failure and automatically reconfigure the system to bypass failed items using a voting scheme.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] This is used with complex computing systems that are linked.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Internet routing is derived from early work by Birman and Joseph in this area.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Active redundancy may introduce more complex failure modes into a system, such as continuous system reconfiguration due to faulty voting logic.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Fault instrumentation can be used in systems with limited redundancy to achieve high availability.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Maintenance actions occur during brief periods of downtime only after a fault indicator activates.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Failure is only significant if this occurs during a mission critical period.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Modeling and simulation is used to evaluate the theoretical reliability for large systems.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] The outcome of this kind of model is used to evaluate different design options.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A model of the entire system is created, and the model is stressed by removing components.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] Redundancy simulation involves the N-x criteria.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] N represents the total number of components in the system. x is the number of components used to stress the system.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] N-1 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where one component is faulted.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] N-2 means the model is stressed by evaluating performance with all possible combinations where two component are faulted simultaneously.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A survey among academic availability experts in 2010 ranked reasons for unavailability of enterprise IT systems.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] A book on the factors themselves was published in 2003.
[src:sre-observability/high-availability] In a 1998 report from IBM Global Services, unavailable systems were estimated to have cost American businesses $4.54 billion in 1996, due to lost productivity and revenues.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] An incident is an event that could lead to loss of, or disruption to, an organization's operations, services, or functions.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] **Incident management** (**IcM**) refers to the activities an organization undertakes to identify, analyze, and correct hazards to prevent future recurrence.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] These incidents within a structured organization are normally dealt with by either an incident response team (IRT), an incident management team (IMT), or Incident Command System (ICS).
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Without effective incident management, an incident can disrupt business operations, information security, IT systems, employees, customers, or other vital business functions.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] An incident is an event that may lead to the loss of, or disruption to, an organization's operations, services or functions.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Incident management (IcM) is a term describing the activities of an organization to identify, analyze, and correct hazards to prevent a future re-occurrence.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] If not managed, an incident can escalate into an emergency, crisis or disaster.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Incident management is therefore the process of limiting the potential disruption caused by such an event, followed by a return to business as usual.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Physical incident management is the real-time response that may last for hours, days, or longer.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The United Kingdom Cabinet Office has produced the National Recovery Guidance (NRG), which is aimed at local responders as part of the implementation of the Civil Contingencies Act 2004 (CCA).
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] It describes the response as the following: "Response encompasses the actions taken to deal with the immediate effects of an emergency.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] In many scenarios, it is likely to be relatively short and to last for a matter of hours or days – rapid implementation of arrangements for collaboration, coordination and communication is, therefore, vital.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Response encompasses the effort to deal not only with the direct effects of the emergency itself (eg fighting fires, rescuing individuals) but also the indirect effects (eg disruption, media interest)".
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] This again shows the importance of not just good planning but the effective allocation of resources to treat the risk.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Incident management in critical infrastructure environments involves coordinated response activities designed to protect essential services whose disruption may impact public safety, economic stability, or national security.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Unlike incident management in purely informational or corporate IT contexts, critical infrastructure incidents often involve operational technology, physical processes, safety systems, and regulatory obligations.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Critical infrastructure incident management typically emphasizes early detection, structured escalation, cross-functional coordination, and continuity of operations.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Incidents may originate from cyber events, physical failures, human error, natural hazards, or combined (hybrid) causes, requiring integrated response across engineering, operations, security, executive leadership, and external authorities.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Because infrastructure sectors are highly interdependent, incident management approaches in these environments often account for cascading effects across energy, communications, transportation, healthcare, and other essential services.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] As a result, planning and response activities commonly incorporate predefined roles, decision authorities, communication protocols, and recovery objectives aligned with safety and resilience requirements.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Today, an important role is played by a Computer Security Incident Response Team (CSIRT), due to the rise of internet crime, and is a common example of an incident faced by companies in developed nations all across the world.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] For example, if an organization discovers that an intruder has gained unauthorized access to a computer system, the CSIRT would analyze the situation, determine the breadth of the compromise, and take corrective action.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Currently, over half of the world's hacking attempts on Trans National Corporations (TNCs) have taken place in North America (57%).
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] A Computer Security Incident Response team can provide a secure environment for an organization, and has become a large part of the design of many modern networking teams.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Incidents within a structured organization are normally dealt with by either an incident response team (IRT), or an incident management team (IMT).
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] These are often designated beforehand or during the event and are placed in control of the organization while the incident is being addressed, to restore normal functions.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The incident commander manages the response to a security incident and leads the members of the incident response team(s) through the process, as defined by the Incident Command System (ICS).
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Usually, as part of the wider management process in private organizations, incident management is followed by post-incident analysis where it is determined why the incident happened despite precautions and controls.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] This analysis is normally overseen by the leaders of the organization, with the view of preventing a repetition of the incident through precautionary measures and often changes in policy.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] This information is then used as feedback to further develop the security policy and/or its practical implementation.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] In the United States, the National Incident Management System, developed by the Department of Homeland Security, integrates effective practices in emergency management into a comprehensive national framework.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] This often results in a higher level of contingency planning, exercise and training, as well as an evaluation of the management of the incident.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Incident management frameworks for critical infrastructure commonly follow a lifecycle-based approach that includes incident detection, classification, response coordination, containment, recovery, and post-incident review.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] These frameworks are designed to support timely decision-making while balancing safety, operational continuity, and regulatory compliance.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] In critical infrastructure contexts, such frameworks often integrate elements from emergency management systems, cybersecurity incident response practices, and operational risk management models.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The goal is to enable organizations to respond effectively under high-consequence conditions while maintaining control over complex technical and organizational dependencies.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Practitioner-oriented literature provides detailed guidance on applying lifecycle-based incident management frameworks within industrial and critical infrastructure environments, including considerations for operational technology, safety, and cross-sector coordination.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] During the root cause analysis, human factors should be assessed.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] James Reason conducted a study into the understanding of adverse effects of human factors.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The study found that major incident investigations, such as Piper Alpha and Kings Cross Underground Fire, made it clear that the causes of the accidents were distributed widely within and outside the organization.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] There are two types of events: active failure—an action that has immediate effects and has the likelihood to cause an accident—and latent or delayed action—events can take years to have an effect and are usually combined with triggering events that then cause the accident.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Latent failures are created as the result of decisions taken at the higher echelons of an organisation.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Their damaging consequences may lie dormant for a long time, only becoming evident when they combine with local triggering factors (e.g., the spring tide, the loading difficulties at Zeebrugge harbour, etc.) to breach the system's defences.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Decisions taken in the higher echelons of an organization can trigger the events towards an accident becoming more likely, the planning, scheduling, forecasting, designing, policymaking, etc., can have a slow burning effect.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The actual unsafe act that triggers an accident can be traced back through the organization and the subsequent failures can be exposed, showing the accumulation of latent failures within the system as a whole that led to the accident becoming more likely and ultimately happening.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Better improvement action can be applied, and reduce the likelihood of the event happening again.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] Incident management is an important part of IT service management (ITSM) process area.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The first goal of the incident management process is to restore a normal service operation as quickly as possible and to minimize the impact on business operations, thus ensuring that the best possible levels of service quality and availability are maintained.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] 'Normal service operation' is defined here as service operation within service-level agreement (SLA).
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] It is one process area within the broader ITIL and ISO 20000 environment.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] an unplanned interruption to an IT service or reduction in the quality of an IT service or a failure of a Configuration Item that has not yet impacted an IT service (for example failure of one disk from a mirror set).
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The ITIL incident management process *ensures that normal service operation is restored as quickly as possible and the business impact is minimized.* **ITIL Service Operation*.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The HIPAA Breach Notification Rule further requires notification to affected individuals within 60 days when unsecured protected health information is compromised, with breaches affecting 500 or more individuals reported to HHS and the media.
[src:sre-observability/incident-management] The proposed rule also mandates annual testing and revision of incident response and contingency plans.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Planning includes arranging for backup sites, whether they are "hot" (operating prior to a disaster), "warm" (ready to begin operating), or "cold" (requires substantial work to begin operating), and standby sites with hardware as needed for continuity.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] In 2008, the British Standards Institution launched a specific standard supporting Business Continuity Standard BS 25999, titled BS25777, specifically to align computer continuity with business continuity.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The **Recovery Time Objective (RTO)** is the targeted duration of time and a service level within which a business process must be restored after a disruption in order to avoid a break in business continuity.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] According to business continuity planning methodology, the RTO is established during the business impact analysis (BIA) by the owner(s) of the process, including identifying time frames for alternate or manual workarounds.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The limits of acceptable or "tolerable" ITSC performance are measured by RTO and RPO in terms of time lost from normal business process functioning and data lost or not backed up during that period.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The business continuity group conducts timed rehearsals (or actuals), during which RTA gets determined and refined as needed.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] A **Recovery Point Objective (RPO)** is the maximum acceptable interval during which transactional data is lost from an IT service.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] For example, if RPO is measured in minutes, then in practice, off-site mirrored backups must be continuously maintained as a daily off-site backup will not suffice.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] A recovery that is not instantaneous restores transactional data over some interval without incurring significant risks or losses.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] RPO measures the maximum time in which recent data might have been permanently lost and not a direct measure of loss quantity.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] For instance, if the BC plan is to restore up to the last available backup, then the RPO is the interval between such backups.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] RPO is not determined by the existing backup regime.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Instead BIA determines RPO for each service.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] When off-site data is required, the period during which data might be lost may start when backups are prepared, not when the backups are secured off-site.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The recovery metrics can be converted to/used alongside failure metrics.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Common measurements include mean time between failures (MTBF), mean time to first failure (MTFF), mean time to repair (MTTR), and mean down time (MDT).
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] A data synchronization point is the point at which a backup is completed.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] It halts update processing while a disk-to-disk copy is completed.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The backup copy reflects the earlier version of the copy operation; not when the data is copied to tape or transmitted elsewhere.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] RTO and the RPO must be balanced, taking business risk into account, along with other system design criteria.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] RPO is tied to the times backups are secured offsite.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Sending synchronous copies to an offsite mirror allows for most unforeseen events.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The use of physical transportation for tapes (or other transportable media) is common.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Recovery can be activated at a predetermined site.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Shared offsite space and hardware complete the package.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] For high volumes of high-value transaction data, hardware can be split across multiple sites.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Planning for disaster recovery and information technology (IT) developed in the mid to late 1970s as computer center managers began to recognize the dependence of their organizations on their computer systems.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] At that time, most systems were batch-oriented mainframes.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] An offsite mainframe could be loaded from backup tapes pending recovery of the primary site; downtime was relatively less critical.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The disaster recovery industry developed to provide backup computer centers.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Sungard Availability Services was one of the earliest such centers, located in Sri Lanka (1978).
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] During the 1980s and 90s, computing grew exponentially, including internal corporate timesharing, online data entry and real-time processing.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Availability of IT systems became more important.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Regulatory agencies became involved; availability objectives of 2, 3, 4 or 5 nines (99.999%) were often mandated, and high-availability solutions for hot-site facilities were sought.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] IT service continuity became essential as part of Business Continuity Management (BCM) and Information Security Management (ISM) as specified in ISO/IEC 27001 and ISO 22301 respectively.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The rise of cloud computing since 2010 created new opportunities for system resiliency.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Service providers absorbed the responsibility for maintaining high service levels, including availability and reliability.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] They offered highly resilient network designs.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Recovery as a Service (RaaS) is widely available and promoted by the Cloud Security Alliance.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Disasters can be the result of three broad categories of threats and hazards.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Preparedness measures for all categories and types of disasters fall into the five mission areas of prevention, protection, mitigation, response, and recovery.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Research supports the idea that implementing a more holistic pre-disaster planning approach is more cost-effective.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Every $1 spent on hazard mitigation (such as a disaster recovery plan) saves society $4 in response and recovery costs.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] As IT systems have become increasingly critical to the smooth operation of a company, and arguably the economy as a whole, the importance of ensuring the continued operation of those systems, and their rapid recovery, has increased.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Control measures are steps or mechanisms that can reduce or eliminate threats.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The choice of mechanisms is reflected in a disaster recovery plan (DRP).
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Control measures can be classified as controls aimed at preventing an event from occurring, controls aimed at detecting or discovering unwanted events, and controls aimed at correcting or restoring the system after a disaster or an event.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] These controls are documented and exercised regularly using so-called "DR tests".
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The disaster recovery strategy derives from the business continuity plan.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Metrics for business processes are then mapped to systems and infrastructure.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] A cost-benefit analysis highlights which disaster recovery measures are appropriate.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Different strategies make sense based on the cost of downtime compared to the cost of implementing a particular strategy.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Disaster recovery as a service (DRaaS) is an arrangement with a third party vendor to perform some or all DR functions for scenarios such as power outages, equipment failures, cyber attacks, and natural disasters.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] **Regular testing**: Regular testing of the disaster recovery plan can verify its effectiveness and identify any weaknesses or gaps.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] **Clear roles and permissions**: It should be clearly defined who is authorized to execute the disaster recovery plan, with separate access and permissions for these individuals.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Implementing a clear separation of permissions between those who can execute the recovery and those who have access to backup data helps minimize the risk of unauthorized actions.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] **Documentation**: The plan should be well-documented and easy-to-follow to ensure that operators can effectively follow it during stressful situations.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] Several regulatory frameworks mandate disaster recovery capabilities for organizations handling sensitive data.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] In the healthcare sector, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) Security Rule requires covered entities and business associates to establish disaster recovery plans as part of the contingency planning standard (45 CFR 164.308(a)(7)).
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] This includes procedures to restore any loss of data, alongside requirements for data backup plans, emergency mode operation plans, and periodic testing and revision of contingency procedures.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] A December 2024 Notice of Proposed Rulemaking (NPRM) to update the HIPAA Security Rule proposes significantly expanded disaster recovery requirements, including a mandate to restore critical systems and data within 72 hours of an outage.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] The proposed rule also requires criticality analyses to prioritize system restoration order, regular testing of disaster recovery plans, and separate technical controls for backup and recovery systems.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] These requirements were influenced by large-scale incidents such as the 2024 Change Healthcare cyberattack, which disrupted claims processing and payment systems across the U.S. healthcare system for weeks.
[src:sre-observability/it-disaster-recovery] In the financial sector, the Federal Financial Institutions Examination Council (FFIEC) requires financial institutions to maintain and test business continuity and disaster recovery plans, with specific expectations for recovery time objectives based on the criticality of business functions.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] The primary drivers for log management implementations are concerns about security, system and network operations (such as system or network administration) and regulatory compliance.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] Logs are generated by nearly every computing device, and can often be directed to different locations both on a local file system or remote system.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] Users and potential users of log management may purchase complete commercial tools or build their own log-management and intelligence tools, assembling the functionality from various open-source components, or acquire (sub-)systems from commercial vendors.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] Log management is a complicated process and organizations often make mistakes while approaching it.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] Logging can produce technical information usable for the maintenance of applications or websites.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] Organizations can use different log-analyzers for analyzing the logs of devices in the security perimeter, typically aiming to identify patterns of attack on the perimeter infrastructure of the organization.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] Organizations may mandate logging to identify the access and usage of confidential data within the security perimeter.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] A log analyzer can also track and monitor the performance and availability of systems at the level of the enterprise, especially of those information assets whose availability organizations regard as vital.
[src:sre-observability/log-management] Organizations may integrate the logs of various business applications into an enterprise log manager for a better value proposition.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] A **service-level agreement** (**SLA**) is an agreement, typically a binding contract, between a service provider and a customer that define particular aspects of the service – such as quality of service, availability, responsibilities – as terms of contract.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] SLAs are commonly used in the technology industry, and often contain specific service-level objectives for defined service level indicators, such as mean time between failures, mean time to repair, mean time to recovery, network throughput, jitter, uptime, first-call resolution, and turnaround time.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Unlike traditional contracts, SLAs often require parties involved to meet regularly to create an open forum for communication, apply rewards and penalties for performance, and leave room for periodic revisitation to make changes.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] SLAs may be supported by operational-level agreements, or OLAs.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Since the late 1980s SLAs have been used by fixed-line telecom operators.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Larger organizations often maintain many SLAs internally, such that two different units in an organization script an SLA with one unit being the customer and another being the service provider.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] This practice helps to maintain the same quality of service amongst different units in the organization and also across multiple locations of the organization.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] This internal scripting of SLA also helps to compare the quality of service between an in-house department and an external service provider.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] The output received by the customer as a result of the service provided is the main focus of the service level agreement.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] It is not uncommon for an internet backbone service provider (or network service provider) to explicitly state its SLA on its website.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Telecommunications Act of 1996 does not expressly mandate that companies have SLAs, but it does provide a framework for firms to do so in Sections 251 and 252.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Section 252(c)(1) for example ("Duty to Negotiate") requires incumbent local exchange carriers (ILECs) to negotiate in good faith about matters such as resale and access to rights of way.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] New emerging technologies such as 5G bring new complexities to the network operators.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] With more stringent SLAs and customer expectations, problem resolutions must be prioritized based on impacted subscribers.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] For fixed networks subscribers, service modeling appears to be one of the most suitable ways to effectively monitor SLA's and ensure they are met.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] A **web service level agreement** (**WSLA**) is a standard for service level agreement compliance monitoring of web services.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] It allows authors to specify the performance metrics associated with a web service application, desired performance targets, and actions that should be performed when performance is not met.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] WSLA Language Specification, version 1.0 was published by IBM in 2001.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] The underlying benefit of cloud computing is shared resources, which are supported by the underlying nature of a shared infrastructure environment.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Thus, SLAs span across the cloud and are offered by service providers as a service-based agreements rather than a customer-based agreements.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Measuring, monitoring and reporting on cloud performance is based on the end UX or their ability to consume resources.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] The downside of cloud computing relative to SLAs is the difficulty in determining the root cause of service interruptions due to the complex nature of the environment.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] As applications are moved from dedicated hardware into the cloud, they need to achieve the same even more demanding levels of service than classical installations.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] SLAs for cloud services focus on characteristics of the data center and more recently include characteristics of the network (see carrier cloud) to support end-to-end SLAs.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Any SLA management strategy considers two well-differentiated phases: negotiating the contract and monitoring its fulfillment in real-time.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Thus, SLA management encompasses the SLA contract definition: the basic schema with the QoS parameters; SLA negotiation; SLA monitoring; SLA violation detection; and SLA enforcement—according to defined policies.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] The main point is to build a new layer upon the grid, cloud, or SOA middleware able to create a negotiation mechanism between the providers and consumers of services.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] An example is the EU–funded Framework 7 research project, SLA@SOI, which is researching aspects of multi-level, multi-provider SLAs within service-oriented infrastructure and cloud computing, while another EU-funded project, VISION Cloud, has provided results concerning content-oriented SLAs.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] FP7 IRMOS also investigated aspects of translating application-level SLA terms to resource-based attributes to bridge the gap between client-side expectations and cloud-provider resource-management mechanisms.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] A summary of the results of various research projects in the area of SLAs (ranging from specifications to monitoring, management and enforcement) has been provided by the European Commission.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Outsourcing involves the transfer of responsibility from an organization to a supplier.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] This new arrangement is managed through a contract that may include one or more SLAs.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] The contract may involve financial penalties and the right to terminate if any of the SLA metrics are consistently missed.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] The setting, tracking and managing SLAs is an important part of the outsourcing relationship management (ORM) discipline.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-agreement] Specific SLAs are typically negotiated upfront as part of the outsourcing contract and used as one of the primary tools of outsourcing governance.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] A **service-level objective** (**SLO**) is a target value or range of values for a service level that is measured by an SLI.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] An SLO is a key element of a service-level agreement (SLA) between a service provider and a customer.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] SLOs are agreed upon as a means of measuring the performance of the service provider and are outlined as a way of avoiding disputes between the two parties based on misunderstanding.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] There is often confusion in the use of SLAs and SLOs.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] The SLA is the entire agreement that specifies what service is to be provided, how it is supported, times, locations, costs, performance, and responsibilities of the parties involved.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] SLOs are specific measurable characteristics of the SLA such as availability, throughput, frequency, response time, or quality.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] These SLOs together are meant to define the expected service between the provider and the customer and vary depending on the service's urgency, resources, and budget.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] SLOs provide a quantitative means to define the level of service a customer can expect from a provider.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] The SLO are formed by setting goals for metrics (commonly called service level indicators, SLIs).
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] As an example, an availability SLO may be defined as the expected measured value of an availability SLI over a prescribed duration (e.g. four weeks).
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] The availability SLI used will vary based on the nature and architecture of the service.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] For example, a simple web service might use the ratio of successful responses served vs the total number of valid requests received.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] While Andrieux et al. define the SLO as "the quality of service aspect of the agreement.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] Syntactically, it is an assertion over the terms of the agreement as well as such qualities as date and time".
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] Keller and Ludwig more concisely define an SLO as "commitment to maintain a particular state of the service in a given period" with respect to the state of the SLA parameters.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] Keller and Ludwig go on to state that while service providers will most often be the lead entity in taking on SLOs there is no firm definition as such and any entity can be responsible for an SLO.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] Optionally an EvaluationEvent maybe assigned to the SLO, an EvaluationEvent is defined as the measure by which the SLO will be checked to see whether it's meeting the expression.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] SLOs should generally be specified in terms of an achievement value or service level, a target measurement, a measurement period, and where and how they are measured.
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] As an example, "90% of calls to the helpdesk should be answered in less than 20 seconds measured over a one-month period as reported by the ACD system".
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] Results can be reported as a percent of time that the target answer time was achieved and then compared to the desired service level (90%).
[src:sre-observability/service-level-objective] The SLO term is found in various scientific papers, for instance in the reference architecture of the SLA@SOI project, and it is used in the Open Grid Forum document on WS-Agreement.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] A **single point of failure** (**SPOF**) is a part of a system that would stop the entire system from working if it were to fail.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] The term single point of failure implies that there is no backup or redundant option that would enable the system to continue to function without it.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] SPOFs are undesirable in any system with a goal of high availability or reliability, be it a business practice, software application, or other industrial system.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] If there is a SPOF present in a system, it produces a potential interruption to the system that is substantially more disruptive than an error would be elsewhere in the system.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Systems can be made robust by adding redundancy in all potential SPOFs.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Redundancy can be achieved at various levels.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] The assessment of a potential SPOF involves identifying the critical components of a complex system that would provoke a total systems failure in case of malfunction.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Highly reliable systems should not rely on any such individual component.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] For instance, the owner of a small tree care company may own only one woodchipper.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] If the chipper breaks, they may be unable to complete their current job and may have to cancel future jobs until they can obtain a replacement.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] The owner could prepare for this in multiple ways.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] The owner of the tree care company may have spare parts ready for the repair of the wood chipper, in case it fails.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] At a higher level, they may have a second wood chipper that they can bring to the job site.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Finally, at the highest level, they may have enough equipment available to completely replace everything at the work site in the case of multiple failures.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] A fault-tolerant computer system can be achieved at the internal component level, at the system level (multiple machines), or site level (replication).
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] One would normally deploy a load balancer to ensure high availability for a server cluster at the system level.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] In a high-availability server cluster, each individual server may attain internal component redundancy by having multiple power supplies, hard drives, and other components.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] System-level redundancy could be obtained by having spare servers waiting to take on the work of another server if it fails.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Since a data center is often a support center for other operations, such as business logic, it represents a potential SPOF in itself.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Thus, at the site level, the entire cluster may be replicated at another location, where it can be accessed in case the primary location becomes unavailable.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] This is typically addressed as part of an IT disaster recovery program.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] While previously the solution to this SPOF was physical duplication of clusters, the high demand for this duplication led multiple businesses to outsource duplication to 3rd parties using cloud computing.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] It has been argued by scholars, however, that doing so simply moves the SPOF and may even increase the likelihood of a failure or cyberattack.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Paul Baran and Donald Davies developed packet switching, a key part of "survivable communications networks".
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Such networks – including ARPANET and the Internet – are designed to have no single point of failure.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Multiple paths between any two points on the network allow those points to continue communicating with each other, the packets "routing around" damage, even after any single failure of any one particular path or any one intermediate node.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] In software engineering, a **bottleneck** occurs when the capacity of an application or a computer system is limited by a single component.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] The bottleneck has the lowest throughput of all parts of the transaction path.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] A common example is when a used programming language is capable of parallel processing, but a given snippet of code has several independent processes run sequentially rather than simultaneously.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Tracking down bottlenecks (sometimes known as *hot spots* – sections of the code that execute most frequently – i.e., have the highest execution count) is called performance analysis.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Reduction is usually achieved with the help of specialized tools, known as performance analyzers or profilers.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] The objective is to make those particular sections of code perform as fast as possible to improve overall algorithmic efficiency.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] A vulnerability or security exploit in just one component can compromise an entire system.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] One of the largest concerns in computer security is attempting to eliminate SPOFs without sacrificing too much convenience to the user.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] With the invention and popularization of the Internet, several systems became connected to the broader world through many difficult-to-secure connections.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] While companies have developed a number of solutions to this, the most consistent form of SPOFs in complex systems tends to remain user error, either by accidental mishandling by an operator or outside interference through phishing attacks.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] The concept of a single point of failure has also been applied to fields outside of engineering, computers, and networking, such as corporate supply chain management and transportation management.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Design structures that create single points of failure include bottlenecks and series circuits (in contrast to parallel circuits).
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] The concept of a single point of failure has also been applied to the intelligence field, and the processes of intelligence.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] Edward Snowden talked of the dangers of being what he described as "the single point of failure" – the sole repository of information.
[src:sre-observability/single-point-of-failure] A component of a life-support system that would constitute a single point of failure would be required to be extremely reliable.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Site Reliability Engineering originated at Google with Benjamin Treynor Sloss, who founded SRE team in 2003.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] The concept expanded within the software development industry, leading various companies to employ site reliability engineers.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] By March 2016, Google had more than 1,000 site reliability engineers on staff.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Dedicated SRE teams are common at larger web development companies.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] In middle-sized and smaller companies, DevOps teams sometimes perform SRE, as well.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Organizations that have adopted the concept include Airbnb, Dropbox, IBM, LinkedIn, Netflix, and Wikimedia.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Site reliability engineers (SREs) are responsible for a combination of system availability, latency, performance, efficiency, change management, monitoring, emergency response, and capacity planning.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] SREs often have backgrounds in software engineering, systems engineering, and/or system administration.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] The focuses of SRE include automation, system design, and improvements to system resilience.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] SRE is considered a specific implementation of DevOps; focusing specifically on building reliable systems, whereas DevOps covers a broader scope of operations.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Despite having different focuses, some companies have rebranded their operations teams to SRE teams.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams collaborate with other departments within organizations to guide the implementation of the mentioned principles.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Kitchen Sink refers to the expansive and often unbounded scope of services and workflows that SRE teams oversee.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Unlike traditional roles with clearly defined boundaries, SREs are tasked with various responsibilities, including system performance optimization, incident management, and automation.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] This approach allows SREs to address multiple challenges, ensuring that systems run efficiently and evolve in response to changing demands and complexities.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Infrastructure SRE teams focus on maintaining and improving the reliability of systems that support other teams' workflows.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] While they sometimes collaborate with platform engineering teams, their primary responsibility is ensuring up-time, performance, and efficiency.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Platform teams, on the other hand, primarily develop the software and systems used across the organization.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] While reliability is a goal for both, platform teams prioritize creating and maintaining the tools and services used by internal stakeholders, whereas Infrastructure SRE teams are tasked with ensuring those systems run smoothly and meet reliability standards.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams utilize a variety of tools with the aim of measuring, maintaining, and enhancing system reliability.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] These tools play a role in monitoring performance, identifying issues, and facilitating proactive maintenance.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] For instance, Nagios Core is commonly employed for system monitoring and alerting, while Prometheus (software) is frequently used for collecting and querying metrics in cloud-native environments.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] SRE teams dedicated to specific products or applications are common in large organizations.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] These teams are responsible for ensuring the reliability, scalability, and performance of key services.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] In larger companies, it's typical to have multiple SRE teams, each focusing on different products or applications, ensuring that each area receives specialized attention to meet performance and availability targets.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] In an embedded model, individual SREs or small SRE pairs are integrated within software engineering teams.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] These SREs collaborate with developers, applying core SRE principles—such as automation, monitoring, and incident response—directly to the software development lifecycle.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] This approach aims to enhance reliability, performance, and collaboration between SREs and developers.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Consulting SRE teams specialize in advising organizations on the implementation of SRE principles and practices.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Typically composed of seasoned SREs with a history across various implementations, these teams provide insights and guidance for specific organizational needs.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] In large organizations that have adopted SRE, a hybrid model is common.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] This model includes various implementations, such as multiple Product/Application SRE teams dedicated to addressing the specific reliability needs of different products.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] An Infrastructure SRE team may collaborate with a Platform engineering group to achieve shared reliability goals for a unified platform that supports all products and applications.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] Since 2014, the USENIX organization has hosted the annual SREcon conference, bringing together site reliability engineers from various industries.
[src:sre-observability/site-reliability-engineering] This conference is a platform for professionals to share knowledge, explore effective practices, and discuss trends in site reliability engineering.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Logs that record program usage (such as a server log) or operating-system events primarily of interest to a system administrator (see for example *Event Viewer*) fall into a terminological gray area.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Tracing is primarily used for anomaly detection, fault analysis, debugging or diagnostic purposes in distributed software systems, such as microservices or serverless functions.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Software tracing is a tool for developers to gather information for debugging.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] This information is used both during development cycles and post-release.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Unlike event logging, software tracing usually does not have the concept of a "class" of event or an "event code".
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] OpenTelemetry is a CNCF open source project that provides comprehensive support for distributed tracing.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Some vendors including Datadog, Dynatrace, New Relic, Splunk also offer tracing SaaS services.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Google and Meta have developed their own tracing frameworks, named Dapper and Canopy respectively.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] In operating systems, tracing can be used in situations (such as booting) where some of the technologies used to provide event logging may not be available.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Linux offers system-level and user-level tracing capabilities with kernel markers and LTTng. ftrace also supports Linux kernel tracing. syslog is another tool in various operating systems for logging and tracing system messages.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] FreeBSD and SmartOS employ DTrace for tracing in both user space and kernel space.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] In embedded software, tracing also requires special techniques for efficient instrumentation and logging and low CPU overhead.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Trace generation of method calls can be done with source code instrumentation, runtime information collection, or under debugger control.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Tracing macros, aspect-oriented programming and related instrumentation techniques can be employed.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Libraries used in source code send data to an agent or directly to the collection component.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] To model execution trees, ISVis converts a rooted tree into a directed acyclic graph while Jinsight utilizes the call frame principle to gather and represent cumulative information about traces.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] The primary visualization method is the swimlane view, which is exemplified by tools like Jaeger and often includes annotations and key-value attributes.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Despite its widespread use, this design lacks rigorous justification and users frequently face challenges like missing features and confusing navigation.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Alternatives to swimlane views exist, like Jaeger’s service dependency view or SkyWalking’s List, Tree, and Table views.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Aggregate visualizations are also used for analyzing large volumes of traces, with systems like Canopy offering queryable metrics and Jaeger providing trace comparison features.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Event logging provides system administrators with information useful for diagnostics and auditing.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] The different classes of events that will be logged, as well as what details will appear in the event messages, are often considered early in the development cycle.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Many event logging technologies allow or even require each class of event to be assigned a unique "code", which is used by the event logging software or a separate viewer (e.g., Event Viewer) to format and output a human-readable message.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] This facilitates localization and allows system administrators to more easily obtain information on problems that occur.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Because event logging is used to log high-level information (often failure information), performance of the logging implementation is often less important.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] A special concern, preventing duplicate events from being recorded "too often" is taken care of through event throttling.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Difficulties in making a clear distinction between event logging and software tracing arise from the fact that some of the same technologies are used for both, and further because many of the criteria that distinguish between the two are continuous rather than discrete.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Enabling or disabling tracing during runtime often necessitates the inclusion of extra data in the binary.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] This can lead to performance degradation, even when tracing is not active.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] The overhead of tracing depends on the used framework and the activated features; in production servers, there is a trade-off between how fine-grained the tracing is and the incurred overhead.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] If tracing is enabled or disabled at compile-time, collecting trace data from a client's system hinges on their willingness and capability to install a version of the software specifically enabled for tracing, and subsequently replicate the issue.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Tracing in software typically demands high standards of robustness, not only in the accuracy and reliability of the trace output but also in ensuring that the process being traced remains uninterrupted.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] Given its low-level nature, tracing can generate a large volume of messages.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] To mitigate performance issues, it's often necessary to have the option to deactivate software tracing, either at the time of compilation or during run-time.
[src:sre-observability/tracing-software] In proprietary software, tracing data may include sensitive information about the product's source code.
